  "opinion": "As a carpenter in Chicago with a background shaped by my father’s PhD and mother’s primary school education, I’ve seen how science and craftsmanship intersect in daily life. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to see themselves reflected in the tools they use. I’ve noticed that in my own community, women often feel excluded from technical fields because they’re told their roles are ‘not for them.’ My depression makes me reflect deeply on this: when kids grow up believing they can’t do science, they never try. We should address it not with big policies, but with small, personal changes. For example, when I volunteer at the community center, I make sure to encourage girls to ask questions about how things work, without judgment. It’s about creating spaces where curiosity isn’t punished by gender stereotypes. The gap isn’t inherent—it’s built. And fixing it starts with listening to those who’ve been silenced, like the women who’ve worked in science but were pushed aside by outdated practices. I’ve seen it firsthand in my neighborhood: when a local teacher stopped teaching physics because she felt unsupported, it hurt the whole community. Addressing the gap means supporting those who want to learn, not just those who fit a mold. It’s about making science accessible to everyone, so that when a girl looks at a wrench or a microscope, she sees herself in it.",
